- Triangular numbers: 1, 3, 6, 10, 15, 21, 28, 36, 45, 55, 66, 78, 91

Now, the pronic numbers less than 100 are:

(Note: 0 is sometimes considered pronic, but since the question asks for numbers less than 100, and pronic numbers start from 0, I will include 0 unless specified otherwise.)

- 6 (triangular, hexagonal, pronic)

136: The most well-known video games that are proven to be NP-complete include the following: Generalized version of the Traveling Salesman Problem in the context of certain game maps
Generalized version of the Knapsack Problem applied to resource management in strategy games
Generalized Sudoku puzzles, which are NP-complete when considering arbitrary grid sizes and constraints
The problem of determining whether a player can reach a certain state in generalized versions of the game Connect Four
The generalized version of the Hamiltonian Path problem as it applies to certain puzzle games
The problem of solving generalized instances of the game of Minesweeper, where the grid size and number of mines are arbitrary
The problem of solving generalized versions of the game of Tetris, specifically in terms of fitting arbitrary sequences of pieces into a given grid
The problem of determining whether a certain configuration can be achieved in generalized versions of the game of Sokoban
The problem of solving generalized versions of the game of Nonograms or Picross puzzles
The problem of finding a winning strategy in generalized versions of certain turn-based strategy games like Hex or certain variants of Go, when played on arbitrary large boards
The problem of solving generalized versions of the game of Lights Out, where the grid size is arbitrary and the goal is to turn all lights off
The problem of solving generalized versions of the game of Peg Solitaire, when the board size and configuration are arbitrary
The problem of solving generalized versions of the game of 8 Queens or N Queens puzzles, which are NP-complete for certain variants involving constraints
The problem of solving generalized versions of the game of Battleship, where the placement of ships and grid size are arbitrary
The problem of solving generalized versions of the game of Matchstick puzzles, involving optimal removal of matchsticks to achieve a certain shape or number of matches
The problem of solving generalized versions of the game of Puzzle Bobble or Bubble Shooter, in terms of optimal shot sequences for arbitrary configurations.

139: The wars that took place in South America include the War of the Pacific, the Chaco War, the Paraguayan Civil War, the Colombian Civil War, the Ecuadorian-Peruvian War, the Cisplatine War, the Argentine Civil Wars, the Falklands War, and various indigenous conflicts such as the Mapuche resistance.
145: SPSS was originally developed by Stanford University students Norman H. Nie, C. Hadlai "Tex" Hull, and Dale H. Bent in 1968. The software was created to facilitate statistical analysis for social science research. In 2009, IBM Corporation acquired the rights to SPSS, and it is now known as IBM SPSS Statistics.
